		<!-- Help tags -->
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_WONDER_ARDL_IVANFORT_HELP">
			<Text>+150 city hitpoints and +15 [ICON_STRENGTH] city strength. +1 [ICON_HAPPINESS_1] Happiness from every Castle in the Empire. +1 [ICON_PRODUCTION] Production, [ICON_FAITH] Faith, and [ICON_GOLD] Gold for every 5 Citizens in this city.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Requires Security.</Text>
		</Row>
		<!-- Quote tags -->
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_WONDER_ARDL_IVANFORT_QUOTE">
			<Text>[NEWLINE]
				“... from Russia I didn’t bring out a single happy memory, only sad, tragic ones. The nightmare of pogroms, the brutality of Cossacks charging young Socialists, fear, shrieks of terror ...”
				—Golda Meir (1898–1978)[NEWLINE]
			</Text>
		</Row>
		<!-- Pedia tags -->
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_WONDER_ARDL_IVANFORT_PEDIA">
			<Text>Ivangorod Fortress was established during the reign of Ivan III in 1492, intended to reaffirm Muscovy's access to the Baltic Sea and to form a bulwark against the Teutonic Order, being built opposite the powerful Teutonic Hermann Castle. The fortress eventually grew into the town of Ivangorod, and the structures of the fort were gradually expanded and strengthened.[1] Ivangorod Fortress was controlled by Sweden after the end of the Livonian War in 1583, changing hands numerous times during conflicts and border shifts over the following centuries. Following World War I, the fortress was used as a POW repatriation camp from 1920-21. After World War II, the fortress returned to permanent Russian rule via the Soviet IVANFORTion. Today, Ivangorod Fortress is a museum and a tourist attraction.  -WIKIPEDIA.</Text>
		</Row>
	</Language_en_US>

